{"key":"processedPost-11475545","value":{"id":11475545,"first":11475444,"last":11475913,"when":1258505838,"utime":"11/18/09 02:57 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Ive had coffee grinds sitting in a bucket with the lid closed for awhile (weeks).</blockquote><br />Not good.&nbsp; Always dry them completely and store in an open container to prevent molds and bacteria.&nbsp; If they're wet at all or smell like anything but coffee, I'd toss them and get fresh ones.<br /><blockquote>Quote:<br />I wanted to add them to coir and have them be pasteurized with the coir (by adding boiling water to the coir in a bucket then putting a lid on the bucket).</blockquote><br />That isn't pasteurization, it's partial sterilization and a poor method at that.&nbsp; The material gets above pasteurization temps at first, but before the hour is up, drops well below pasteurization temperature.&nbsp; It works with coir because you could use no pasteurization at all with coir and succeed.&nbsp; Used with coffee, straw, compost, manure, etc., it's going to have a high failure rate.<br />To pasteurize, heat your material to 140F/60C and keep it there for an hour to 90 minutes.<br />RR","title":"Re: Coffee Grinds. Toss?"}}